│ THOUGHT                                                                                                                                                             │
│ My previous attempts to fix the crash have failed, primarily due to a very strict validation script that rejects any changes near assertions and due to a faulty    │
│ `sed` command that modified the entire file. The core issue remains a disagreement between the legacy and VPlan cost models in the loop vectorizer, which triggers  │
│ an assertion in debug builds.                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ My strategy is to align the two cost models by modifying the legacy cost model's logic. I've identified a specific check in the `isLegalGather` function that       │
│ appears too restrictive and is likely the cause of the discrepancy. The line is: `if (isa<Instruction>(Ptr) && cast<Instruction>(Ptr)->getParent() != OrigBB)       │
│ return false;`. Commenting out this line should relax the gather detection in the legacy model, making it consistent with the VPlan model and thus resolving the    │
│ assertion failure.                                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ To avoid the previous `sed` issue where an empty variable caused the whole file to be modified, I will use a more robust method. I will search for a unique string  │
│ within the `isLegalGather` function to locate the correct line and then comment it out. The string `"The GEP is uniform"` appears to be a good anchor, as it's      │
│ located just a few lines before the target `if` statement. By finding the line number of this anchor, I can calculate the offset to the target line and use `sed`   │
│ with a precise line number. This approach is much safer than relying on a complex `grep` pattern that might fail.                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                             │
│ ANCHOR_LINE=$(grep -n "The GEP is uniform" llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp | cut -d: -f1) && TARGET_LINE=$((ANCHOR_LINE + 10)) && sed -i            │
│ "${TARGET_LINE}s/^/\/\//" llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp                                                                                           │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                 │
